    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-09-09T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-09-09T14:00:00-05:00" n="21"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d21">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.4231/1236: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Canada</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Armour</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Ottawa</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-09-09T15:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 9, 1935—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 4:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>94. Dr. Skelton<note n="13" xml:id="d21fn13">Canadian Under Secretary of State
                        for External Affairs.</note> informs me that the Canadian Government’s
                    official list of articles on which the same [<hi rend="italic">sic</hi>]
                    reductions under trade agreement will be presented by Canadian Legation Tuesday
                    September 10th. He informs me that list differs somewhat from that already
                    informally discussed, consideration having been given to arguments presented by
                    our representatives. Also certain articles which had not occurred to our
                    Government have been added.</p>
                <p>The concessions which the Canadians are prepared to make on American products are
                    probably being discussed here but they hope to have this list ready by the end
                    of the week before the Prime Minister leaves on his election speaking tour. In
                    studying our list he states that due consideration here also has been given to
                    the arguments ably advanced by our representatives.</p>
                <p>Three notes exchanged between Governments were published by the press this
                    morning. While local press reaction appears fair, Montreal <hi rend="italic"
                        >Gazette</hi> considers the action of Congress in reimposing excise tax on
                    Canadian lumber was a death blow to the negotiations. Skelton assures me
                    attitude of <hi rend="italic">Gazette</hi> should not be taken seriously.
                    Although the leading conservative organ it has consistently opposed the Prime
                    Minister’s reform program and is of course well known as favoring a strong
                    protective policy.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Armour</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
